=E2=80=9Cnorms are much harder to transmit in a distributed =
context=E2=80=9D =E2=80=93 my concern is that open source communities =
practice a certain type of innovation and individuals generate identity =
and respect in a different way from wider society =E2=80=93 maybe?

So will the world of work move towards being one enormous open source =
community =E2=80=93 or is this a red herring?

=20

A few questions about open source communities:

*	How does one generate an identity in an open source community? =
(propose a change which others review and promote / find useful?)
*	How does one generate a reputation in an open source community =
(propose lots of changes which get voted up?)
*	Who decides who sets the rules in an open source community? (is it one =
person one vote, do the cool kids get together and decide who is in =
charge, do the people with reputation get together and exercise super =
votes?)
*	In real lives (certainly in mine) great ideas normally come from =
randomly shooting the shit with someone, often only tangentially about =
the subject of the idea. What is the parallel in an open source =
community? And do open source communities recognise the input of the =
people that were shooting the shit when the idea was formed =E2=80=93 =
but didn=E2=80=99t actually submit it? Its this element of communities =
that often bothers me =E2=80=93 how do we move away from people =
generating their identities on the basis of =E2=80=9Cthat was my =
